******
[2]
Date: 14 Oct 2011
Source: HorseTalk.Co.nz [edited]
http://www.horsetalk.co.nz/news/2011/10/115.shtml


Ticks to blame for horse deaths -- media report
-----------------------------------------------
Ticks are behind the deaths of more than 20 horses at a property at
Kooralbyn, Queensland, The Chronicle reports.

Biosecurity Queensland has yet to released any official word on the
cause of the deaths, but paralysis ticks (_Ixodes holocyclus_) were
among the potential causes under investigation.

Other possibilities include a toxic weed, botulism and deliberate
poisoning.
The death toll now stands at 23 horses, Biosecurity Queensland said
yesterday, leaving just 2 of the original 25 horses alive. It said
test results were expected within a few days. The Chronicle said
necropsy results revealed tick poisoning was behind the deaths.

It said post-mortem examinations by Biosecurity Queensland had ruled
out deliberate poisoning and botulism.

The surviving horses -- 4 at the time of the report -- had been given
anti-tick serum, the newspaper said.

